I would say in a\nvery much beta state.
It's more of a sharing\nrather than a conclusion.
A sampling rather\nthan a composition.
So I'm going to begin Hot\n& Wet: The Equatorial City
and the Architectures\nof Atmosphere
as I did in the original 2015\npresentation, with a 1956 quote
from Maxwell Fry and Jane\nDrew: "The rapid increase
in population over the\narea of the tropics
presents itself to the world as\na problem of utmost gravity."
What was a pressing\nconcern over 60 years ago
in that quote has become\nan issue of critical--
if not dire-- importance today.
As a large portion of the\nworld's growing population
occurs in the tropical belt,\nthe resulting urbanization,
dramatic territorial\ntransformation,
and rising temperatures\nare altering
the equator in substantial\nand unforeseen ways.
When I conceived Hot & Wet,\nI looked to other architects
whose own grand tours seemed\ninstrumental in shaping
their design sensibilities.
Of course, Le Corbusier\ntraveled through Europe
between 1907 and 1911.
His outcomes being published\nas his Journey to the East.
Or Luke Hahn's own trajectory\ntaking a linear path
terminating in Karnak\nin southern Egypt.
As Michael said, the Wheelwright\nin its original incarnation
encouraged these\ntemperate-centric arcs
of travel--
enabling Paul Rudolph,\nI.M. Pei, and others
whose own parallel\ntrajectory largely
orbited around\nthe Mediterranean.
For me, I saw this as a\nkind of deeply indebted
temperate prejudice built\ninto the grand tour.
And by extension\nrooted in a latitude
of European and American\narchitectural discourse.
And being that I now\ncall the equator home,
I started to look to\nothers for guides.
The amazing travels of\nAlfred Russell Wallace
and his specimen collecting\nacross the Malay Archipelago
suggested another arc of travel\nlooking about the equator.
Not for architecture,\nin his case,
but for the natural world.
We could say eyes wide open.
Or Alexander Humboldt\nwith the equator
in his horizon in his\nfive year expedition
to the equatorial\nregions of South America.
The outcomes of his research\nas isothermal classifications
locate and make distinct the\nhot and wet areas of the world.
And define the area of\nwhere I practice today.
What's interesting in\nHumboldt's original conception
is that the area\nof the temperate
are relatively striated\nto a fine degree.
Understood maybe\nin great detail.
Yet, in contrast, we can see\nthe equatorial region remains
a large pink zone.
It's a crude understanding\nof the equator
as a single climate.
It's a temperate narcissism\neven for Humboldt--
a holdover from pejorative\nunderstandings from Aristotle
onward.
From the temperate\nvantage point,
the equatorial has always\nbeen negatively described.
Perimedes divided the\nearth into five zones--
two arctic, ones two temperate\nones, and a single burned zone.
To Pliny the Elder,\na Greek geographer,
describing the tropics\nas a ring of fire.
To Aristotle in his\ntext Meteoralogica--
claiming the tropics\nas a torrid zone--
asserting that the area was\njust too hot for inhabitation.
Or to Mark\n[? rebullious' ?] drawings
from the fifth century, where\nthe red fire-like center is
later reincarnated in Humboldt's\niteration now as pink.
Temperate ideas about climate\nand the resulting architecture
and urban configurations\nI would say
are largely\nself-referential, reinforcing
one's own climactic\nparticularities as ideal.
And if you think this history\nof temperate prejudice
is an old problem, we can\nfind built-in partialities
in contemporary writing\nabout the equator.
For example, in the 2016\nClimates: Architecture
in the Planetary Imaginary--
reviewing the climate\nof the equator
is a problem to be rectified.
In Eva Horn's\ninteresting essay--
Air Conditioning:\nTaming the Climate
as a Dream of Civilisation--
she begins, and I\nquote, "I had no idea
the tropics were that hot.
When I first exited the sliding\nglass doors at Changi Airport
Singapore--" that\'s\nwhere I live,
by the way "--I stepped into\nsomething I had never quite
experienced before.
This was not air as I knew it.
It was more like a\nsemi-liquid medium--
a gel, moist, hot, suffocating.
Something you inhale but that\nenvelops your body like a mass.
Impatiently dragging my\nluggage through that mass
toward the taxi,\nI started panting.
My head, my hands,\nswollen from heat.
The driver opened the\ndoor and I tumbled
in to the refrigerated\ninside of the car.
For a moment I felt relief as\nmy body escaped the suffocating
atmosphere."
Living in the suffocating\nhot and wet as I do,
I've tried to look at\natmosphere not as a problem
to be rectified, or tempered, or\nturned into a northern climate
through techno science\nor air conditioning,
but rather as a\nkind of potential.
To use another lens that\nconsiders atmosphere--
the hot air, the thick, the\ngel, the moist, the wet,
the semi-liquid, the\nmoldy, the stained--
all as mediums to work\nwith just as architects
normatively work with\nspace, material, and light.
The torrid has also been\ntraditionally understood
by tempered eyes as a place\nof pestilence and fear.
Or a territory of abundance\nand exuberant resources
ready for extraction.
Think colonialism or\neven tropical tourism.
Could we refigure a way\nto conceive architecture
and the equatorial city--
maybe in a more\nrobust and mature way?
My lens for my travels\nfocused on a moment
when modernism confronted the\ntropical right before the onset
of air conditioning.
When the friction of the equator\nrubbed into architecture.
When cities were\nusing urban artifacts
as symbols of independence for\nthe crafting of new societies
and new nations.
This moment-- we could say\nfrom the late 1930s to the end
of the 1970s--
is a tremendously rich\nand complex. period.
A golden moment of sorts.
And clearly the ghosts of\nMaxwell Fry, Jane Drew,
Otto Koenigsberger,\namong many others
are present in the research.
My travel looks upon this\nmoment not as a historian
but as an architect\npeering into the near past
to project a future--
for maybe selfishly\nmy design practice--
looking at artifacts\nas vessels that
embed the contestation\nbetween city, space, material,
atmosphere, maybe even politics\nand capital wrapped together.
My torrid tour took me\nnot only to five cities,
but eventually to eight\nacross the equator.
Four in Southeast Asia, one\nin India, one in Africa,
and two in South America.
I traveled close to\n100,000 kilometers,
