My travel began as a\nseries of small arcs
from Singapore\nemanating outward.
Each one gaining in\ndistance following
the winds of the Northeast\nMonsoon east to west,
returning to Singapore\nafter each tour.
Semarang to Jakarta\nand Yogyakarta
and Bandung in between.
To Palembang and to KL and\nthen Pondicherry, Accra,
and then Sao Paulo and Joao.
I traveled back multiple\ntimes to cities maybe
nearer than far.
I would also say the\nhot and wet implies
a climactic specificity.
Typically with temperatures\nabove 80 degrees Fahrenheit,
usually in the mid\n90s in the afternoon.
With humidity exceeding 80%,\nan annual rainfall of a meter
or more per year, with some\ncities exceeding 2.5 meters--
that's eight feet-- of rain.
Numerical quantification\ngives only a partial sense
of this atmosphere for it\nreally needs to be felt,
walked through,\ninhaled, experienced.
Not simply understood as data.
So I was interested not in\na strict maybe climactic
geography--
Sao Paulo was really\nkind of an outlier--
but a range of\nhot and wet climes
that contained a spectrum of\narchitectural ideas suited
to their specific urban and\natmospheric environments.
I also want to say this\nisn't a solo project.
