My travels commenced in the\neastern city of Semarang
in Indonesia.
A relatively small\nsoutheast Asian locale
of 1.7 million people.
Seven degrees south of the\nequator on the southern edge
of the Java Sea.
Semarang is really two cities.
A northern flat\ncity, a coastal city
with it's southern\ncity as a tail--
that you can see here--
is one of topography class\nand contrasting status.
The flat city runs out as a\nblanket of roofs, streets,
and courtyards.
A desakota in visible\nterms, were landscape, roof,
and object blend together in\na continuous field of urbanism
and vegetation, motorbike and\nshop, house and school, Mosque
and factory.
The topographic city\nfolds in on itself--
filling valley and\nhill alike, making
visible the class differences\nby elevation and section
rather than by\nplanned proximity.
Large volumes dominate\nthe volcanic hills
as they look to the growing city\nthrough the heavy atmosphere
of the afternoon sun.
Semarang is also a city\nof trade and markets.
Its access to the\nhinterlands of central Java
link it to the trade\nroutes of Asia.
Historically, this\nhas been reflected
in the large Chinese diaspora\nand its own Chinatown.
As is its demographic\nmix combining Malay,
Javanese, Arabic, and\nIndian ethnicities
throughout the city's fabric.
Here we can see the\nedges of Chinatown
in a series of middle class\nparty wall shop houses--
located just adjacent\nto the Dutch Kota
which was an important\nVOC and colonial trading
port during colonialism.
Jewelry and gold markets\nare adjacent to food
and dry good markets.
And here in this original\ndistrict now in decline,
the city moves further\nand further inland--
retreating from the\nfloods of a rising sea.
The buildings here have\nbeen largely abandoned
except for the perimeter\nshops on the ground floor
and a lively street\nlevel daytime trading.
The developmental\npressures of Semarang
are great as this city continues\nto grow outward and upward.
The density of the shop\nhouses are being transformed
into the rise of mid-scale\ntowers that have begun to make
their mark in the distance--
transforming the\ncontinuous large roof
into the city of elevations.
As an extension of\nthis trading fabric--
and central to\nSemarang's identity
as the role of the market--
a typological big roof that\naggregates and condenses
the diversity of\nsmaller traders,
shopkeepers, and merchants\nunder a single and identifiable
surface.
In Semarang there are\nover 20 large markets,
each one serving a neighborhood\nat the district scale.
The largest and most dramatic\nbig roof is the Pasar Johar,
built in 1932 by the\nDutch-Indonesian,
Herman Thomas Karsten--
an engineer and\nplanner by profession.
At the time of its\nopening, the Pasar Johar
was claimed to be the\nlargest covered market in all
of Southeast Asia.
And like all good\ntorrid grand tours--
a little drama\nbegins my research.
After receiving Michael's\ncall sometime in April,
I think it was, of 2015--
and before I could even get\non a plane to Semarang--
this vessel of study\nsuffered a horrible fire.
Fire ripped through the\narchitecture in May 9, 2015,
rendering the market to ashes.
It was a great way to\nbegin my research--
all going up in smoke.
But I was determined\nto go, and when
I arrived the market was still\nsmoldering with ash, soot,
and the remains of\nlivestock and livelihoods
strewn about the floor.
The fire caused over 4,000\ntraders to lose their venues,
with many more\ninformal kiosks being
erased in the fire's wake.
Because of this\nprogrammatic erasure,
the architecture was rendered\nas foreground rather than
background, and its role as a\ndramatic atmospheric framework
became even more self-evident.
The market is composed\nof three sections
oriented on a north-south axis.
Rectangular in plan\nwith a slight chamfer
for the open air market at the\nmost southern of the squares.
While the market scale is vast\ncompared to the small scale
aggregation of the Chinatown\nfabric just adjacent.
In the large open courtyard--\nhaving just burned--
contained a series\nof steel structures
of pitched and flat roofs\nwith small dry good merchants
beneath.
You can see Raman here--
digging through the remains of\nthe market on the lower right,
his stall having been\nincinerated just weeks before.
The central square extends\nthe roof across the square,
covering it with four\nlarge concrete planes
all in equal size.
The market that had just been\nbefore under the concrete roof
quickly re-established itself\nexactly around the perimeter
of Pasar Johar, encasing the\nembers in a ring of trading.
The burned market\nis to the left--
which is here-- and the\nnewly established market
was established under a series\nof orange and blue tarpaulins.
We could say a\nsymbol of resilience
if there ever was one.
The displaced merchants rebuilt\ntheir networks as quickly
as the market burned.
For their livelihood\nis intricately
linked to the central\ntrading area of Semarang.
Back under the burned canopy,\ntraces of each merchant store
littered the plan--
ceramic, pottery, and\ndishware are all visible
as though it was an\narchaeological site.
Flanking ramps on the\nnorth and south elevations
allowed goods to move easily--
vertically-- for Karsten had a\ndeeply embedded social agenda
in the architecture.
The market was, as\nI understand it,
designed for the small-scale\nlocal and largely female
merchant class even from\nits incarnation in 1932.
A series of cast-raised\nplinths allowed merchants
to place their goods off\nfrom the contaminated floor.
The large two story columns\nmarch across the double volume
from veranda to volume alike.
The central square was\nonce the wet market--
where we can imagine smells of\nraw meat, fish, and vegetables
percolating through the space\nrequiring the most ventilation.
Each wing contains 24 columns\nrising above the floor
about 8 and 1/2 meters.
The volume of contained\nair is grand in proportion.
A large swimming pool of thick\nJavanese air and moisture
slowly moving from\nstreet inward and upward.
One cannot help but make\nparallels between the Johnson
Wax headquarters designed by\nFrank Lloyd Wright from 1939.
Only that Karsten's\nPasar Johar was completed
some seven years earlier.
The similarities are\nshockingly close--
interior veranda,\ndouble height space,
and marching capitals alike.
We could also trace the\nwork to Robert Maillart's
first mushroom slab structure\nin the warehouse Giesshubel
in Zurich from 1910.
Or his grain storage of the\nSwiss Confederation in Altdorf
from 1912.
Karsten clearly appears to have\nadopted Maillart's techniques--
articulating column to\ncapital in a smooth arc,
while capital to slab\ninterfaces contain a series
of stepped transition planes.
Karsten also removed\nthe continuous perimeter
to allow for a full ventilation\nof the interior space
laterally.
Inside the light oscillates\nbetween the intensity
and the bleaching quality\nof the equatorial sun,
and the dark undersides\nof the lower market.
Sound of the nearby\nmosque, roaring motorbikes,
and street-side merchants--
rooster caws\nincluded-- percolate
through this roof assemblage.
Traces of the\nrattan formwork are
imprinted into the\nunderside surface
of the concrete between\nthe oculi, which illuminate
and ventilate simultaneously.
So you can see the rattan was\npart of the original formwork.
The big roof is layered--
stacked upon stack\nslipping over one another--
bunker-like as a\nseries of layers
evacuating hot air and smell.
Side vents suck in air, light,\nand sound penetrating deep
into the underside\nof the market.
This architecture works with\npressure in a figural sense
to squeeze and open, push and\npull, shade and illuminate
in a calibration of air itself.
For the Pasar Johar, air\nand all of its contaminants
are as mediums and fundamental\ncomponents of the architecture.
I've worked with other\ndevices of capture
from thermal imaging--
where traces of the\ncolumns shown in green
are contrasted to a\nsurprisingly cool roof--
and developed a\nlanguage of drawing
