on architecture.
Especially at the detail.
For much of equatorial\narchitecture,
the deployment of\nthe overhang and roof
conceals the\nelevational complexity.
And can only be\nunderstood by looking up
through the worm's eye\nas a primary device
of understanding.
Karsten used the layering of\nplanes of concrete horizontals
to make up the roof.
But it is also the\nthick massive assembly
of air captured by the perimeter\nveranda and oculi that layer up
to construct the architecture.
The volume of air between\nthe roof and ground--
I'm thinking of a large maybe\npillow here being compressed--
under pressure that\npushes air out.
It's an exhalation.
An architecture that\ngasps and breathes.
The Pasar Johar is the\nmost dramatic and formal
of the Karsten markets.
I visited four of\nthem in my travels.
Even in its derelict state,\nit creates a very real sense
of inhalation and exhaust.
As though the building\nmoves air in and out,
pumping through a gigantic\narchitectural lung.
It's also a lung for the city.
A center of positive\nfriction and a pole
of gravity for trading and\nbusiness and livelihood
that anchors the city.
Of course, this\nisn't just a story
about atmosphere\nwithin the market,
but also about power\nstruggle for the market.
The frictions at the city\ncenter and the political agency
of the merchant class\nas older artifacts
confront developmental\npressures.
Throughout my\ntravels to Semarang,
