Karsten's worked as a\nplanner and architectist
throughout Indonesia.
And I traced his influence like\na detective to the Pasar Cinde,
in the city of Palembang on\nthe grand island of Sumatra.
My interest was to see the large\ntwo-story market in operation--
to view the convergence of the\narchitectural, the atmosphere,
and the inhabitational that\nI was denied in Semarang.
As I caught onto the winds that\ntraced westward to Pasar Cinde,
it to--
as I was soon to find out--\nwas to suffer a similar fate.
Palembang, a growing city of 1.5\nmillion, is a city of export.
A city of moving hinterland\nresources to river
to ocean ship.
It's a [? map ?] urbanism of\nroofs with tremendous traffic
and an upward middle class\nmade visible by its automobile
ownership and the\nunder-construction elevated
metro train system above.
The Pasar Cinde, dwarfed by\nthe coming infrastructure
is a vessel for the contestation\nof population growth,
developmentalism, and the\nlegacies of modernism.
This is the Pasar Cinde\non the bottom here.
I arrived just in time in 2016\nto find a reductive Karsten--
understood to be an\nadapted design by
Abu [? cousonno ?]\n[inaudible],, the head
of Public Works Departments\nof Independent Indonesia.
Skylights as simple\nrectangles, fluted columns,
perimeter verandas, all speak\nwith a Pasar Johar sensibility.
The market was full\nof smell and sound,
lively in the trade of the day.
The tropes of Karsten are\nthroughout-- column capitals
that merge slab to\nvertical in an almost
stalactite configuration.
The business was brisk, the\narchitecture crude, layered,
simple, and direct.
Basements had little\nof the ventilation
of Pasar Johar or the\nnatural illumination,
though the scale and size\nof the columns were robust.
A burly physicality to\nthe transfer of load.
The clear story layering\naccommodated ventilation
about the veranda,\nyet the market
foreshadowed the\ncoming realities
of developmental forces.
Just two months ago\nthe market is now
not only abandoned, but in the\nprocess of being destroyed.
It is as though the\nfate of Pasar Johar
has percolated\nwestward to Palembang,
as another city transforms from\nthe horizontal to the vertical.
Where the logics of walkable\nstories, small-scale merchants,
and the big roof are replaced\nby boxes, sealed envelopes,
and large-scale capital\nseeking rental income
on a return on investment.
The ruining of Pasar Cinde\nhappened without fire.
Believed to be due to its\nsmaller internal population
and thus diminutive\npolitical force.
But it's ruined no less--
an eviction in spatial\neconomic in historical terms.
In Palembang-- like Semarang--
