Jakarta, in many\nways, is further
along this transformational\npath from the horizontal
to the vertical.
And the ventilated\nto the conditioned.
The city defies\neasy categorization
being the largest in Indonesia--
the capital of the nation.
It is the center of\npolitical and financial power
for the vast archipelago.
Jakarta's larger region\nis a rolling environment--
a village, dense city,\nland form, and agriculture.
The origin of Terry McGee's\ntext as the original Desakota--
that traces in plan from\nJava's northern coastline
along a series of 14\nrivers percolating
southward to the volcanoes of\nMount Sorak and Mount Gede.
The city has grown in bands\nof expansion southward
and its current\nform is a collision
of informal settlements,\nkampungs, urban villages,
middle class aggregations,\nhighways, commercial towers,
and super-scaled\nshopping complexes
all in close proximity.
Here growth occurs in\nsprouts and volcanoes,
erupting side-by-side\nto small singular homes.
The kampungs largely penetrated\nby motorbike, bicycle, or foot
produce the consistent ground\nof Jakarta punctuated by larger
figures of modernisation--
national monuments,\ntransportation,
infrastructure, and\nobject buildings.
For the vast majority\nof the residential--
architecture opens to\npedestrian streets of one
to two meters in width.
Front terraces merge\nwith passageways.
Inhabitants bound\nfrom another interior
to another across\nthe ground plane
of political and\nspatial porosity.
And when it floods--
a liquid porosity,\nall the more dramatic.
This foamy-like\nspace coats Jakarta
as a field of inhabitation.
The contemporary city which\nemerges from this foam
is not a model of integration\nin interpenetrability
but of large scale bubbles.
Towers and blocks of\nmassive proportion
contain a plethora of uses\nin inhabitational practices.
They are self-contained\nclimates unto themselves,
accessible by air\nconditioned automobiles.
Searched and sanctified by\nsecurity guards and gates,
perimeter private roads, and\nlarge-scale parking decks,
only after traversing\nJakarta's infamous traffic
where even president Jokowi\nwalks in the sun for two hours
to reach his meetings.
Just happened a few months ago.
The scale of such\nbubbles can be massive.
For example, in the grand\nIndonesia shopping town
that spans almost 7 million\nsquare feet a single building.
It's about a million more than\nthe United States Pentagon.
The adjacent kampung of\nthe streets of Mata Pura
just to the south rise only\na story or two or three.
Crossing from one spatial\nexperience to another
is a radical transformation\nof scale, density, porosity,
and organization.
My interest in Jakarta was\nnot in this shocking spectrum,
nor in the informal settlement\nto occupy the horizontal.
But rather in the mid-rise\nbuilding known as the Sequis
Center located south\nof Jalan Sudirman.
It was completed in 1978,\ndesigned by the architect
Hassan Roland Vogel--
supposedly of Swiss origin.
Located in the bottom\nright of this photograph,
the diminutive 12-story\nmiddle scale block
sits on a northwest orientation\nover the large boulevard.
To the left, the large civic\npark and national stadiums
of independence--
built for the 4th Asian games\nfrom 1962 under [? serkarno ?]
and financed by\nthe Soviet Union--
dot the landscape.
The Sequis Center has been\ndwarfed by its larger neighbors
as capital has\naggregated in the area,
and towers have grown\nlarger and more massive.
The building's\ndistinctive feature
is a perimeter envelope of\nparabolic fiber-reinforced
concrete, whose deep\nspatial envelope serves
as a thermal buffer\nseparating heat
gained from the building proper.
The fiber panels\nprotrude outward,
also shedding the interior\nfrom the ubiquitous monsoon
downpour.
The mass barely protrudes from\nthe large-scale vegetation
along Jalan Sudirman, yet\nsuggests an alternative vision
of architecture\nfrom its neighbors--
a hairy, opaque\naesthetic that works
with atmosphere expressively.
From above the building\nreads as a solid mass,
an assemblage of the\npointed and pitched roof.
A common trope of Indonesian\nvernacular architecture
that in this case had been\nminiaturized, multiplied,
and arrayed across the\nbuilding in elevation.
From below the\nbuilding's porosity
is revealed a window wall\nglazed without coatings
or reflective films,\nas the role of shading
is done through solidity itself.
The building and elevation reads\nas a series of subtle slits--
a strong equatorial aesthetic\nof opacity and materiality--
across the vertical plane\nthat is a resistance
to the temperate\nand the transparent
immediately adjacent.
The dramatics of the equatorial\nsun play across the envelope.
Looking out through\nthe eye-like profiles,
the view peers down to\nthe vegetated ground.
By doing so the windows shed\nthe normative requirements
of expensive embedded\ntechnologies,
shifting the role of\ntechnoscience and performance
to a simple material with\nexpressive architectural
agency.
The building stands as a vessel.
An urban artifact\nsymbolizing-- and maybe
even monumentalizing--\nan alternative vision
for the equatorial city.
Dark rather than light.
Deep rather than thick.
Perforated rather than closed.
Material rather\nthan transparent.
But growing in the background--
the new Sequis Center\nTower by the same developer
speaks of another\nmore common narrative
in the equatorial city.
The new building designed by\nKPF is a glass-enclosed block
