Located four hours\nsouth of Chennai
on the east coast of India,\nfacing the Bay of Bengal
and the city of Pondicherry.
The small city of\n3/4 of a million
was a colony of the French East\nIndia Company from 1674 onward.
The legacies of\nFrench colonial rule
are imprinted deep into the\ncity's formal structure.
A grid plan running\nperpendicular
to the sea with an\noblong ring road
marks the separation between\nthe formal French corridor
and its expanding\nTamil periphery.
The city is split between\nthis visible French influence
and the higher densities\nof aggregation to the west.
Between neoclassical buildings\nwith generous courtyards
and the party wall\nconstruction of density
where the majority of the\nresidential and business areas
are located.
The city is not a\ncity of roofs as we
found in Semarang or\nPalembang, nor elevations
as in Jakarta or KL, but a\nseries of mid-scale masses.
Three to five stories in\nheight, a tightly-compacted
high-density arrangement.
The gridded city has a\nstrange emptied feeling.
For over 100 buildings are\nnow owned by the Sri Aurobindo
Ashram--
one of the most important\nashrams in India.
Imagine a city of\nwhispering yogis--
this is Pondicherry.
The Golconde dormitory\ndesigned by Antonin Raymond,
Francoise Sommer,\nGeorge Nakashima
between 1935 and 1942, marks\nthe first modern cast-in-place
building in India.
The design deploys a series\nof tropical modern motifs
that we found in KL, though\nthey were developed here almost
20 years earlier.
A bar building displaced about\na vertical stair core, situated
precisely along a\neast-west axis in alignment
to the tropical sun path.
The collision of the building\nagainst a tilting city grid
appears object-like,\nyet a perimeter wall
with a single entry door\ncamouflages the intelligence
behind.
The superimposition of\nthe two orientations
creates three courtyards--
two northern hot courtyards\nand a southern cool courtyard.
The northern courtyard heats\nup in the afternoon creating
a low pressure, while the\nsouthern courtyard as shaded
creates a high pressure because\nof his lower temperature.
The differential\nbetween these volumes
creates a velocity of\nair moving laterally
across the architecture.
The building still operates\nas a dormitory to the ashram
and getting access was\nextremely cumbersome.
With profuse self-chastisement\nin the basement
as a prerequisite\nfor my entry, I
ended up bowing for\nforgiveness to a sin
I wasn't quite aware of to a\nvery large rotund Indian woman
named Suman.
It was really hard to\nget into this building.
The asbestos cement\nscreen set in a grid form
is all in off-white concrete.
Surprisingly thin and easy to\nmove by cast brass hardware.
Two gaps on the\nground floor allow air
to move between the bar\nat relatively high speeds,
making it the ideal foyer for\nresting in the hot afternoon.
So there's a gap there\nand there and everyone
sits there to cool off.
Ventilation is throughout,\nproviding shade even
for the casual street-side rest.
Within the architecture\nproper, a lamination
of screen, veranda, corridor, a\nsliding panel, dormitory room,
and window bay all\nfunction holistically.
The finishes are\nlargely natural allowing
the thermal mass\nof each material
to comfort the interior.
Exposed slabs modulate\nair temperature
while dark floors\nminimize glare.
The furniture within the room is\nconstructed in teak and rattan,
speaking of a language of moving\nair around and about the body.
Designed by George\nNakashima, it directly
foreshadows his future\nas a furniture maker
in Pennsylvania.
The staircase-- open in the\ncenter and ventilated on both
sides--
drives air and light deep\ninto the architecture.
Details are expressive\nand subtle simultaneously.
Even brass inlays-- you can\nsee them in the plaster here--
allow the wall to breathe\nbetween it's hot outside
and cooler inside,\nmitigating thermal expansion
of the plaster itself.
Screens when adjusted\nallow light or view
and can be closed for\nthe tropical rain.
The roof likewise a doubling--
an enlarged tile roof\nwith integrated drainage
and perforated ends\nto cross-ventilate
the main building mass.
The details are exquisite\nin their execution
and the superb upkeep\nthanks to Amra Nemenberry,
who inherited the\ncustodianship from her father--
the original caretaker\nof the building as part
