The building speaks of\nanother important narrative
of contemporary equatorial\nurbanization discussed
during my travels.
The exquisite construction of\nthis building in the late 1930s
sits in contrast to the\nrelatively crude fabrication
recently underway\nin nearby Pondi.
Or in Chennai from\nwhere I landed.
The narrative is\nthat as craftsmen
became replaceable labor, as\nthey saw higher laborers wages
in Dubai, Saudi Arabia, or\nSingapore from the '70s onward.
The result has been that in\nthis part of Tamil, India,
construction knowledge\nhas been emptied out
by the global flows of\ncapital and labor alike.
And the transference\nof expertise
through apprenticeship ruptured.
Today local architects\nclaim that the Golconde
would be near impossible.
For the basic\nbuilding intelligence
has been shipped elsewhere,\nand the knowledge and care
of building exported across\nthe equator without return.
This is a photograph\nin Singapore
of labor coming from India.
We pick up the traces of\nthe Golconde dormitory
in the city of Accra, Ghana--
on the north of the Gulf of\nGuinea, five degrees north
