These are enormous--\nas space itself.
As a separate element\nthe brise soleil
does not transmit heat\nload into the slabs proper.
And it's relatively\nlight color acts
has both a sunshade, light\nshelf, and wind funnels
simultaneously.
This blue netting\nis a new addition.
The building is currently\nveiled to contain the falling
ceramic tiles that were\noriginally deployed
on the concrete to resist\nthe mold and algae.
Though now is a kind\nof hazard to passerbys,
as you can imagine\nthe tiles falling off.
The apartments of a variety\nof one and two units deep,
allow air to move from\none elevation to another.
From the unified deep\nelevation we saw with the blue,
to the melange of\nthe compositional
of the southeastern\nfacade shown here.
The building as a vertical city\nworks as a pole of population--
a barometric vessel of the\ndownward or upward trajectories
of the city's fortune.
Aggregating and\nspilling populations
into the nearby neighborhoods.
In contrasting context from\nthe Edificio Copan building--
the faculty of\narchitecture and urbanism
at the University of Sao Paulo\nis situated in a garden campus
setting.
Designed by Joao Vilanova\nArtigas from '61,
it's located in the western\nside of the city in a canopy
of large rain trees.
Which ironically have\nbeen imported to Singapore
where I live, and populate\nthe majority of the campus
at the National University\nof Singapore where I teach.
The building is stunning\nnot for its large commons
as a social space or the\ndramatic ramps that provide
for vertical circulation.
These are all well known\nin architectural circles.
Nor from the big roof that\noperates as a structure,
drainage, and lighting device.
It's really a super\nstudio imagination
if there ever was one.
But for the subtle details\nof the thick big roof
as a device to\nplunge air vertically
rather than horizontally.
The big roof\nselectively isolates
and modifies\natmosphere filtering
through the architecture.
It's a subtle performance\nlargely overlooked
in published descriptions.
The large studio space is\nreally two double trays.
One is a kind of roof\nand exterior wall,
the second has an\ninterior tray--
an internal wall-- that squeeze\nhot air between the two.
And I'll give you a clue\nof this little trough
that you see along the length.
This trough gives rise\nto the performance
as a gap runs along\nboth the elevations.
And you can see it again here.
Air plunges downward and\nupward through this gap
between those two walls--
an exhausting of moving air\nand sound and smell alike.
The [inaudible] high inner wall\nof the slippage, which is here,
dampens the sound to a whisper--\nso basically air is moving up
and down across\nthese two walls--
while traces of the\ninterior gives clues
to the inhabitation above.
It's as though the architecture\nis a lung that breathes.
Inhaling and exhaling on\na 24 hour student cycle.
A subtle puckering of exterior\nwall to interior kiss--
imagining merging the\ntwo trays together.
And the porosity of the\nentry operates not just
for circulation, but rather\nas a large-scale plunger
that pushes air within.
Exhausting through those\nslots along its perimeter.
The final location I visited\non this long arc of travel
is Joao.
A small city 400 kilometers\nnorthwest of San Paulo.
A city of 150,000 people.
An agricultural town\nreminiscent of the Midwest
in the United States.
