from '73.
The draw bus depot fits into\nthe [? overa ?] of Artigas' work
as the big roof--
as an urban bus exchange--\nnavigating a sloped site
and connecting one block\nto another by architecture.
One city to another\nby transportation.
The large roof of\nArtigas' depot contrast
against the surrounding\nsmaller scale aggregate
fabric and the horizontality\nof the geography.
The city has grown both\nlaterally as well as
vertically.
But it's the large big roof\nthat has a compelling presence,
reinforcing an almost Wrightean\nvision of a broad acre city.
Within the perforation\nof the horizontal plane
by skylights and the formal\nand structural gymnastics
of the column, capital,\nand slab intersect
with the broad and long ramps--
speak of a parallel sensibility\nwith the FAU building.
Air moves laterally\nwhile sunlight
is diffused vertically.
The bus depot is a doubling.
A deep occupiable volume\nof ramps and circulation
as a second story.
Perforated by two\nlarge flanking entries.
One for pedestrian,\nbus, and air alike.
The top roof-- layered above and\nset proud with torque columns--
squeeze air and light between a\nkind of tight 2.7 meter space.
The ramps and openings\nbetween these layers
operate as a thermal\nand circulatory straw--
moving air and people\nacross the topography
and mixing them in a dynamic\nzone of interference.
Pedestrians, cars, streets,\nsidewalks, and busways
all intermingle in this space\nof congestion in compression.
Where people in circulation,\nticketing and selling,
