agricultural\nhinterland of Brazil--
all mix together.
It's a big roof typology.
Not for the buying\nand selling of goods,
but the moving of\nbodies and things.
I see the legacies of\nKarsten in Semarang--
traveling to Joao\nacross the equator--
in an interplay of\nair, atmosphere,
architecture, in the city.
As bookends to my grand\ntour of the equator,
I was impressed\nby the simplicity
and robust physicality of\nthe large roofs of Karsten
and Artigas alike.
The reductive quality of the\nbig roof as a public and social
project, the integration\nof architecture,
the economy of\nmaterial, and the mixing
of architecture, the\ncity, and atmosphere
simultaneously suggest a\ntheory of equatorial porosity
and maybe contamination.
A friction with the expansive\nmediums of architecture
and urbanism alike.
In both Karsten\nand Artigas I find
