A viscous, almost aquatic,\npresence to the air.
Heavy and full of\nphysicality that
is netted by the\narchitecture of the big roof
or between the deep elevation.
Whereas the temperate thickens\nwith stone, masonry, concrete,
or insulation--
or utilizes technology to\nmake separate and distinct
the atmospheres of\ninterior and exterior--
the equatorial medium\nis the hot and wet air.
A vocabulary for\ndesigning architecture
and refiguring the city\nas permeable rather than
separated.
Perforated rather than sealed.
In the cities that\nI traveled to I
found a great and often\nvery intense struggle.
Rapid demographic pressures,\nimpacts of climate change,
and capital aggregation are\ncreating immense pressures
across the equator.
And it's easy to\nsee these places
at sites of temperate fantasy.
For easy importation of\nconstruction systems,
mechanical and\ninfrastructural implants,
and transformations into\nvisions of the global north.
But by resisting\nclimactic replacement
and working where architecture\nconfronts the issues of density
growth and permeability, another\nvision for the equatorial city
is possible.
I've painted through\nthis arc of travel
as though there is a kind of\nlarge meta narrative here.
Maybe in some ways there is--
a narrative of the\ninterplay between modernism,
internationalism, atmosphere,\nand developmental pressure.
This sets the foundation for\nurbanism across the equator.
But it's also a collage\nof the micro narratives--
of friction and struggle, of\ninterference intelligence,
of the equatorial which\nrubs up against the flows
of global homogenisation.
The long histories\nof colonialism
and the contemporary challenges\nof rapid growing cities.
Mid 20th century architecture on\nthe equator offers a complex--
sometimes inspiring and often\nconflicted-- history lesson.
All of which are being\nstill played out today
despite its rapid erasure.
